english:
  title: Record of the Floating Verdure Tower
  author: Hong Gwi-dal
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The streams of Yongju were renowned throughout the southern provinces for their crystalline shallows, and the forests there for their deep, luxuriant depths. In my youth, I studied at the gate of Master Ju, a scholar of that county. Whenever our lessons ended and I found a moment's rest, I would lead my companions to wander between stream and forest. When weariness overtook us, we would cast ourselves upon a guest house and sleep.

    The county sits north of South Mountain and south of North Mountain, surrounded on all sides by verdant peaks. Stepping beyond the gate, clear waters spread like bolts of silk, and across the water, deep forests tower in tangled abundance. Truly, one could call it a place of transcendent beauty. Yet I lamented that the official buildings were cramped and mean, and the towers low and insignificant.

    Years passed. I took service at court, and my feet touched no lake or mountain for more than forty years. When at last I returned, the natural beauty remained unchanged, but the buildings and towers had fallen into such ruin that I could not help but sigh for the mountains and streams.

    In the fourth year of Hongzhi, Magistrate Heo Min of Yangcheon arrived to govern this county. Having already brought prosperity to the people and removed their hardships, and having no further matters to occupy him, he surveyed the beauty of the mountains and streams. Ascending the old tower, he sighed: "Alas! This is precisely what is meant by things not matching their proper place. To have mountains and streams of such beauty, yet buildings so mean—is this not the magistrate's responsibility? And surely, the official residence is not for my personal comfort alone, but serves the royal authority. How could I hesitate?"

    East of the guest house and north of the old tower stood a knoll with a great stone half-buried upon it. The magistrate had the stone excavated and the ground leveled, and upon this spot he built a tower. The central chamber, spanning three bays, serves as a place of public gathering. On the east and west sides stand three chambers each, for ordinary rest and repose. The structure is most magnificent. From it, one gazes down upon the clear streams with bright eyes and uplifted spirit. The verdant hues of the surrounding peaks rise and shimmer, swirling beneath the eaves.

    Thus at last did place and dwelling find harmony. For those charged with governance whose minds grow troubled and whose affairs grow tangled, ascending this tower brings a sudden clearing and sudden awakening. Is this not beneficial?

    Upon completion, word came to me from Magistrate Heo: "The tower is new but as yet unnamed. This was once your cherished place of wandering. Would you not give it a name and write its record? Perhaps the mountains and streams themselves have hopes of you."

    I named it Floating Verdure, recalling what these eyes beheld in years past. And I reflected: "In my youth, before I had yet reached adulthood, I knew the pleasures of stream and forest. Forty years have passed since then. How many magistrates have I known to govern these lands in my absence? Yet none has accomplished this. It fell to our Magistrate Heo to bring it to completion. Do mountains and streams meet with humanity only in certain times?

    "Yet it is true that nothing worthy should be rushed. What matters is that the time should favor it and the person be suited to it. Though mountains and streams may possess great beauty, if the realm be troubled, the fields neglected, and the people sorrowful, how could one find leisure for such work? And if one forced it, would it not be an affliction upon the people?

    "But now a sage ruler dwells above. The people dwell in peace. Virtuous magistrates are stationed in every county. The farmers rest secure in their labors and go forth to their duties as willingly as children obey their fathers. How then could one sit in a ruined tower and a broken hall, ungrateful to mountains and streams?

    "In this single deed of Magistrate Heo, one perceives both the auspicious signs of universal peace and the true heart of the people of this county. How could I fail to record this?"
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Hongzhi was the reign period of the Chenghua Emperor of Ming China (1464-1487). The fourth year would be 1491.
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase 'Floating Verdure' (浮翠) captures both the visual impression of mountain mist creating the illusion of verdure floating beneath the eaves, and the philosophical idea of transient natural beauty.
  - key: ''
    value: The author's reflection on why this work was not accomplished by previous magistrates, followed by his meditation on the proper timing and alignment of opportunity with virtue, reflects the Confucian understanding of governance as dependent on both individual virtue and favorable circumstances.
